go_data.justification: Trim32 is described as an E3 ubiquitin ligase, which implies it enables the transfer of ubiquitin to target proteins.
Trim32 is mentioned in the context of muscle atrophy, indicating its involvement in this process.
Trim32 is stated to be important for the degradation of actin, tropomyosin, and troponins, which are proteins.
Trim32 causes the loss of desmin Z-bands and thin filaments, which are components of the cytoskeleton in muscle cells.
